Here's the writeup:

What it delivers

A high-fidelity editorial landing page for a fictional luxury lifestyle society — Maison d'Argent — rendered as a magazine-grade web experience. Old money aesthetics, private club exclusivity, and print-editorial typography, all in the browser.

You don't get a startup landing page. You get a broadsheet. A typeset masthead with an edition line and founding year. A hero block with display-weight serif headlines and flanking anchor ornaments. A three-column editorial spread with a drop-cap manifesto on the left, a parallax hero frame in the center, and a service directory on the right — each service illustrated with a hand-drawn SVG engraving. Below that: a four-up destination grid, a yacht ownership pitch with a pennant illustration, and a membership enquiry form that generates a reference number on submission. Every section fades in on scroll. Every element is built from scratch.

The core value is this: luxury brand websites are almost always template-driven or agency-bloated. This demonstrates that a single developer can produce an editorial layout with the visual density and typographic care of a Departures spread or a Monocle feature — zero dependencies, zero build tools, zero component libraries.

Core properties

Zero build tooling. No Webpack, no Vite, no npm, no node_modules. React 18 and Babel compile JSX directly in the browser. The entire site runs off a static file server. Drop the folder on Vercel and it deploys.

Typographic system with four pairings. Italiana × Cormorant Garamond (default), Playfair Display × EB Garamond, DM Serif Display × Cormorant, and Libre Caslon Display × Text. Each pairing is a single CSS class on the body — every heading, body paragraph, label, and monospace element responds. The type system isn't decorative — it's the architecture. Display, body, label, and mono are four distinct semantic layers, all switchable at once.

Four complete color palettes. Bone & Ink (warm parchment, dark letterpress), Sepia & Antique (aged paper, deeper gold), Cream & Bordeaux (oxblood accent on cream), and Ink (full dark mode inversion). Every palette is a set of CSS custom properties — paper, paper-deep, paper-edge, ink, ink-soft, ink-mute, rule, accent, gold. The dark mode palette doesn't just invert foreground and background; it re-tunes every opacity, blend mode, and shadow to feel correct on a dark field.

Four masthead treatments. Italic wordmark ("Le Curateur"), Caslon editorial ("The Argent Compendium"), monogram only ("M·A"), and modernist all-caps ("MAISON D ARGENT"). Each treatment changes the headline copy, the tagline, and the typographic styling. The masthead isn't a logo — it's a brand identity system with four distinct editorial voices.

Hand-drawn SVG iconography. Nine service icons — yacht, wellness, tour, event, concierge, dining, estate, wine, art — each drawn as minimal line engravings inside 56×56 bordered frames. No icon library, no font glyphs. Every stroke, hull, mast, fork, wine glass, and globe is authored inline as SVG path data, styled with the current ink color.

Paper grain without images. A CSS-only texture overlay using three layered radial gradients at different densities (3px, 5px, 7px), blended via mix-blend-mode: multiply. In dark mode, it switches to screen blending and reduces opacity. The effect is subtle and resolution-independent — no raster noise, no repeating tile.

Scroll-driven reveal animations. Every major section is wrapped in a .reveal class. An IntersectionObserver triggers at 12% visibility, adding a class that transitions opacity and a 14px vertical shift over 0.9 seconds. Sections materialize as you scroll, one by one, without JavaScript animation libraries.

Parallax on the editorial hero. The center column's hero frame tracks scroll position and applies a gentle vertical offset (±40px range) via a CSS custom property. The effect is scroll-driven but throttled by passive event listeners — no requestAnimationFrame loops, no layout thrash.

Full membership form with confirmation flow. Name, email, phone, city, country, net worth tier, referral source, contact preference (email/phone/concierge), nine interest checkboxes, and a freeform notes field. On submit, the form replaces itself with a centered thank-you panel displaying a generated reference code (MA-XXXX-NNNN). Every input is styled from scratch — underline text fields, custom select arrows, custom radio dots, custom checkboxes with serif checkmarks. Two layout modes: three-column split and single-column stacked.

Ornamental detailing. Double rules below the masthead. Ornament rules with centered glyphs (✦) between sections. A crest block with a monogram inside concentric circles (solid, soft, dashed). A pennant SVG with a compass rose on a flagpole. Anchor icons flanking the hero tagline. Every ornament uses the current palette's ink and gold colors.

Responsive down to mobile. Three breakpoints: full editorial at desktop, two-column reflow at 960px, single-column stack at 600px. The masthead, destination grid, form layout, service grid, and editorial columns all restructure. The type scale uses clamp() throughout — display headlines range from 48px to 112px, section heads from 22px to 28px.

Ships with a tweaks panel. A floating, draggable settings panel — frosted glass with backdrop blur, viewport-clamped positioning, custom scrollbar — lets you switch palette, typography, masthead style, hero photo, and form layout in real time. Every change is instant, no reload. The panel is a reusable component system (TweakSlider, TweakToggle, TweakRadio, TweakSelect, TweakColor, TweakNumber, TweakButton) that can be dropped into any prototype.

What makes it different

It treats brand identity as a design variable, not a fixed asset. Most landing pages ship one look. This ships four mastheads, four type pairings, four palettes, and three hero treatments — all composable. A creative director could sit with a client, open the tweaks panel, and try sixty combinations in a meeting. The site isn't a page; it's a brand exploration tool.

It has the density of print. Three-column editorial layouts, drop caps, double rules, ornamental dividers, engraved icons, crest blocks, pennant illustrations — the visual language is drawn from magazine and broadsheet design, not SaaS templates. Nothing looks like a website. Everything looks like it was typeset.

The form is part of the experience. Most luxury brand forms are afterthoughts — a Typeform embed or a mailto link. This one is styled with the same typographic system as the editorial content. Underline inputs, serif checkmarks, uppercase labels at 10px with 0.28em letter-spacing. The confirmation panel matches the editorial tone. The reference number feels like a receipt from a private club, not a form ID.

Use cases

Luxury brand prototype. A founder or creative director building a members-only club, private travel service, or wealth-adjacent lifestyle brand can use this as a functional prototype — swap the copy, drop in photos, and present to investors or partners. The tweaks panel makes it a presentation tool, not just a mockup.

Editorial design system. The atomic elements — display type scale, body text with drop cap, ornamental rules, SVG icons, crest block, parallax frame, reveal animations, form controls — compose into any editorial layout. A magazine site, a hotel booking page, a wine club, or a real estate brochure could be built from the same parts.

Portfolio showpiece. This project demonstrates editorial typography, CSS architecture (custom properties, palette theming, responsive grids), component design, SVG illustration, scroll-driven animation, and form UX — in a single artifact. It's not a tutorial exercise. It's a production-fidelity editorial interface built without a single dependency.

Design exploration tool. The four-palette × four-type × four-masthead matrix produces dozens of distinct brand identities from the same content. A designer could use this to demonstrate how typographic and chromatic choices shape brand perception — same words, same layout, completely different mood.

Future potential

Real photography. The current build uses labeled placeholder frames with hatched backgrounds and file-spec callouts — ready for art direction. Dropping in actual images (yacht photography, destination aerials, villa interiors) would bring the layout to full production fidelity without touching the code.

CMS integration. The content layer — experiences, destinations, brand copy, form fields — is cleanly separated as JavaScript objects at the top of app.jsx. Wiring it to a headless CMS (Sanity, Contentful, Notion API) would make the copy editable without developer involvement.

Booking and payments. The membership form currently generates a client-side reference number. Adding a backend (Stripe for deposits, a serverless function for email confirmation) would turn this into a working intake funnel. The form already captures net worth tier, referral source, and interest categories — the data model is ready.

Animation polish. The scroll reveals are intentionally restrained. Adding staggered entrance timing for the service list, a slow ken-burns drift on the hero photo, and subtle parallax on the destination cards would push it from editorial to cinematic — without changing the information architecture.

Multi-page expansion. The current single-page layout could extend into a full site: a destinations detail page, a journal/editorial blog, a member portal, an events calendar. The type system, palette theming, and component library already support it — the foundation scales.

How it was built

Designed and developed collaboratively with Claude Code in a continuous session. Human-directed brand vision — the old-money editorial tone, the magazine-format layout, the typographic pairings, the ornamental detailing. Every component authored from scratch through conversation: describe the section, review what's generated, adjust until the typography and spacing feel right. No templates, no UI libraries, no design systems imported. The entire codebase is ~2,000 lines of hand-written JSX and CSS across five files.